teTime":"2019-10-02T19:54:02.762634Z","entity":"article","guid":"e0beaebc-ffe1-494d-a732-4e8d80de107d","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170607-why-printers-add-secret-tracking-dots","modifiedDateTime":"2022-02-24T17:35:36.020582Z","project":"wwverticals","slug":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170607-why-printers-add-secret-tracking-dots","cacheLastUpdated":1665921288107},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old":{"urn":"urn:pubpipe:wwverticals:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old","_id":"62df7f4043d9f46d39486b2e","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"Ageing is not an inevitable fact of life – many animals have already found ways to delay death. Their clues might help us all enjoy longer and healthier lives.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EJust 30 years after the publication of Moby Dick, a group of Alaskan whalers attempted to tame their own ocean giant. Their target was a male bowhead whale, the second largest mammal on Earth. The species were already famed for their amazing longevity: according to Inuit folklore, they could live &ldquo;two human lifetimes&rdquo;, and they were known to escape harpoons with their great strength.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The local Inuit claimed that the whales lived &ldquo;two human lifetimes&rdquo;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThese whalers were armed with the latest technology, however &ndash; a &ldquo;bomb lance&rdquo;, fired with gunpowder on impact to pierce through the thick whale blubber. Yet it was not enough to conquer the whale. Three fragments of the lance caught in its side, but &ndash; like Moby Dick &ndash; it pulled away and escaped with little more than a surface wound.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe whale would continue to roam free for another 120 years, until 2007, when a group of Inupiat hunters finally caught the beast. They even found fragments of the original lance still \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002Fs00300-008-0407-2\"\u003Eembedded in the whale&rsquo;s blubber\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to many estimates, these whales live at least 150 years, and perhaps as long as 210. Apart from slightly leathery skin, a bit of excess blubber, and its battle scars, they show remarkably few ill-effects of long life, however. And that has made them of keen interest to doctors studying ageing.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;They live a lot longer than human beings, yet they are living in the wild, without going to the doctor or any of the perks of human society,&rdquo; says Joao Pedro de Magalhaes at the University of Liverpool. &ldquo;So they must be naturally protected from age-related diseases.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"If we could retard ageing even a little, it would have unprecedented human benefit","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBy studying these whales and other extraordinarily long-lived creatures, de Magalhaes and colleagues hope we can find new medicines that will similarly \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fdirectorsblog.nih.gov\u002F2014\u002F05\u002F08\u002Fcreative-minds-secrets-of-longevity-from-bats-and-rats\u002F\"\u003Eslow down the human body&rsquo;s decay and delay death\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;Ageing is a mystery &ndash; we know relatively little about it compared other biological processes, and yet it&rsquo;s directly the greatest cause of suffering and death in the modern world,&rdquo; says de Magalhaes. &ldquo;If we could retard it even a little, it would have unprecedented human benefit.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVadim Gladyshev at Harvard University agrees. &ldquo;This is the most important biological question, because the majority of chronic human diseases are the consequences of ageing. The way biomedical science is organised, it has mostly focused on particular diseases, like cancer, Alzheimer&rsquo;s, or diabetes,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;But if you delay ageing you could delay the incidence of all these diseases at once.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EVarious factors are thought to \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC2995895\u002F\"\u003Econtribute to ageing\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. First there&rsquo;s the environment: no one can live in a pristine bubble, and so our DNA and other molecular machinery can become slowly damaged by harmful chemicals or radiation. Although our cells have some DIY toolkits that help fix the damage, eventually the devastation could become too widespread, leading to mutations that cause cells to turn into tumours.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWe could also develop problems with our metabolism: like a furnace that needs regular cleaning, our cells produce a host of waste products as they burn energy. As the waste collects over time, it might disrupt crucial biological processes. &ldquo;The amount of damage accumulates and the organism isn&rsquo;t able to cope with it,&rdquo; says Gladyshev.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"You might think that ageing is an unstoppable force &ndash; but there are brakes to slow its progress","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFinally, the body encounters problems regenerating organs: each chromosome has a bundle of DNA at its ends, called telomeres, which act a bit like the plastic tips of a shoelace, to stop it from fraying. The telomeres become shorter each time the cell divides, however, and eventually it could become so short that the cell begins to malfunction, or die. With this wear and tear, we are more vulnerable to various diseases.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethuselah&rsquo;s menagerie\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of which seems like an unstoppable force pushing us towards death &ndash; but several lines of evidence suggest there are brakes that can slow its progress. For instance, a common diabetes drug, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Fnews\u002Fanti-ageing-pill-pushed-as-bona-fide-drug-1.17769\"\u003Emetformin, can modestly slow ageing\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in mice. And simply changing one gene involved in cell metabolism in a roundworm can lead it to live many times longer than its parents; while it is unlikely the same changes would help more complex organisms, it hints that ageing is not beyond our control. &ldquo;Ageing is a surprisingly plastic process that can be manipulated,&rdquo; de Magalhaes says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Natural selection has somehow pushed certain creatures to evolve their own elixir of life","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EScientists like de Magalhaes and Gladyshev are now on the hunt for other candidates, using real-life Methuselahs as their guide. Across mammals alone, expected \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F25677554\"\u003Elifespan can vary 100-fold\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, from shrews that live for no longer than 1.5 years to the bowhead whales that can live for more than 200. It is as if, for various reasons, natural selection has somehow pushed certain creatures to evolve their own elixir of life.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Metformin extends lifespan in mice modestly, but when you look at different species, the capacity of natural selection to extend lifespan is incredibly more powerful,&rdquo; says de Magalhaes. &ldquo;They will have probably evolved entirely different ways of living longer, and resisting cancer and other age-related diseases.&rdquo; And each of those could lead to better medicine. Or as Gladyshev puts it: &ldquo;Nature changes lifespan all the time, so the question is, how does it do it? And can we target those mechanisms, thereby increasing human longevity?&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The Brandt&rsquo;s bat lives more than 40 years, despite weighing little more than a sugar cube","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"calloutBodyHtml":"\u003Cp\u003EThe bowhead whale can live for longer than two centuries, making it the oldest mammal. But how does it compare to other types of organisms?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cul\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EA study comparing the pollen and seeds of bristlecone pines up to 4700 years old found no significant increases in cell mutation rates with age\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EColonial animals like corals can also survive for more than 4000 years. However, individual polyps may live for only a few years\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003EMing the mollusc is the oldest verified solitary animal on record. This ocean quahog was 507 years old when biologists dredged it up from the coastal waters around Iceland in 2006.\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ERead more about the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fearth\u002Fstory\u002F20150622-can-anything-live-forever\"\u003Eanimals and plants that can live forever\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fearth\u002Fstory\u002F20150622-can-anything-live-forever\"\u003E here\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E","calloutSubtitle":"Can any creatures live forever?","calloutTitle":"The immortal zoo","cardType":"CalloutBox","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most interesting creatures are the extreme outliers; single species that seem to outlive even their closest relatives. They are not always as magnificent as the bowhead whale. With its wrinkled, hairless skin, the naked mole rat does not look like a poster child for successful ageing &ndash; yet it lives for up to 30 years, much longer than the two or three years that well-fed house mice can enjoy. In particular, the naked mole rat is unusually resistant to cancer &ndash; no tumours have yet been found in thousands of individuals studied in the lab. Even when they have been bathed in potent carcinogens, they remain cancer-free.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis might be partly explained by the fact that their cells tend to stop growing when \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC2780760\u002F\"\u003Ethey become too dense &ndash; a mechanism that stops tumo\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC2780760\u002F\"\u003Eurs\u003C\u002Fa\u003E from replicating and growing out of control. The trait seems to arise from a \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3720720\u002F\"\u003Eparticularly &ldquo;heavy&rdquo; version of a chemical known as hyaluronan\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. This molecule is part of the scaffolding surrounding cells, and might have originally evolved to make naked mole rat&rsquo;s skin more elastic as they squeezed through their tight burrows. Today, it appears to be part of the signalling that stops cells from multiplying uncontrollably. In other words, even if a mutation would cause a tumour to form, the hyaluronan stops it from developing further.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EGladyshev has also studied Brandt&rsquo;s bat &ndash; a tiny creature that lives for more than 40 years, despite weighing little more than a sugar cube. &ldquo;Considering the size, it&rsquo;s the most extreme case,&rdquo; says Gladyshev. He has found \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Fncomms\u002F2013\u002F130820\u002Fncomms3212\u002Ffull\u002Fncomms3212.html\"\u003Eunusual mutations around its receptors for growth hormone and insulin-like growth factor\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; alterations that could offer further clues about ways to control metabolism in mammals, limiting the damage that normally comes with age.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWould the record-breaking bowhead whale reveal similar insights? The whale&rsquo;s enormous size &ndash; 20 metres long and up to 100 tonnes in weight &ndash; creates some unique challenges that are of particular interest to biologists like de Magalhaes and Gladyshev. For instance, if its cells burnt energy at the same rate as mice cells, the excess heat would boil the surrounding water, so it has evolved to live with a slower metabolism and lower body temperature.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuch a huge body also puts you at enormous risk of cancer, thanks to simple mathematics: the more cells you have, the more likely you are to develop a harmful mutation. (Indeed, one study found that taller people are slightly more likely to \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.thelancet.com\u002Fjournals\u002Flanonc\u002Farticle\u002FPIIS1470-2045%2811%2970154-1\u002Fabstract\"\u003Edevelop cancer than shorter people, for this very reason\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.) And the problems become even greater the longer your life span. &ldquo;When you live longer, you go through more divisions, so the likelihood of cancer increases hugely,&rdquo; says Leonard Nunney at the University of California, Riverside, who researches the evolution of cancer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBased on human rates of cancer, all large whales should all be riddled with tumours \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3060950\u002F\"\u003Ebefore they have even grown up\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; yet they continue to live for at least another century. This fact is known as &ldquo;Peto&rsquo;s Paradox&rdquo;, and it suggests that the whales, like the naked mole rat, have some clever evolutionary tricks to deal with harmful mutations. &ldquo;When put in the context of other animals, they really are outliers,&rdquo; says de Magalhaes. &ldquo;They must have tumour-suppressing mechanisms that we lack.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-18"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-19"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The task was akin to shredding hundreds of thousands of copies of Moby Dick and then pasting the individual sentences back together","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-20"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt was these mechanisms, and more, that de Magalhaes hoped to answer by peering into its genome. Initially, he struggled to find a way to sample the tissue. Eventually, however, he found a team who had already built links with Inuit hunters. To preserve their traditional way of life, indigenous societies around the Arctic are allowed to capture and kill a limited number of bowheads each year. Although they were initially suspicious of outsiders, the hunters eventually agreed for the scientists to sample some of the tissue collected from their kills.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEven once they had collected the material, the team still faced the extraordinary task of building the genetic sequence. Given the enormous volume of data, the task was akin to shredding hundreds of thousands of copies of Moby Dick and then pasting the individual sentences back together into a meaningful order.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC4536333\u002F\"\u003Eresult is a series of leads that might just pave the way for future medicine\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Of particular interest, they saw notable changes on a gene called ERCC1. This gene is known to code for a molecular toolkit that can patch up small areas of damage to the genome. It seems likely that the bowhead&rsquo;s mutation makes it even more efficient at its job, perhaps preventing the build-up of harmful mutations that cause cancer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-21"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-22"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe team also found changes to a gene called PCNA, which is involved in cell proliferation. It codes for a protein that acts as a kind of clamp, holding together the molecular machines that cause DNA to replicate. Bowheads have duplicated regions of the gene, and their mutations seem to help it interact with other parts of the toolkit involved in DNA repair. The team hypothesise that this single change could promote healthier cell growth without the damage that comes with age. Taken with other notable adaptations that might have helped the bowhead mop up cellular stress, these insights offer a first glimpse at the whale&rsquo;s secrets to longevity.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E'Longevity signature'\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcross the Atlantic at Harvard, Gladyshev recently performed his own study of the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC4247388\u002F\"\u003Ebowhead whales&rsquo; &ldquo;transcriptome\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo;; not just studying the genes, but also exploring how active they are. If you can see that certain genes are particularly active, then you know that it too might be playing an important role in ageing. Tellingly, he has found the same kinds of changes to insulin signalling that he also saw in Brandt&rsquo;s bat. &ldquo;It may change the metabolic setup of the cells, so that somehow it is longer-lived,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;though the exact intricacies are still a matter of debate.&rdquo; Together, the results provide a &ldquo;longevity signature&rdquo;, he says, that could then be used to guide future research.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe findings are attracting attention from some of the most important figures in medicine. Francis Collins, the director of the US National Institutes of Health has been impressed, writing that Gladyshev&rsquo;s work brings us &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fdirectorsblog.nih.gov\u002F2014\u002F05\u002F08\u002Fcreative-minds-secrets-of-longevity-from-bats-and-rats\u002F\"\u003Eright up to the threshold of new insights into healthier, longer life\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-23"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The findings are attracting attention from some of the most important figures in medicine","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-24"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOnce over that threshold, there are many potential ways that these findings might improve treatments. Gladyshev suggests that we could see whether diet or exercise programmes could help to shift the body to match the longevity signature of the whale. For example, some have suggested that fasting, or &ldquo;caloric restriction&rdquo; slows ageing processes, and it might be interesting to compare whether it brings the kinds of metabolic changes that help the whale survive for so long. In this way, the bowhead whale could offer immediate guidance for the best ways to life longer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-25"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-26"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAlternatively, these long-lived creatures could inspire some more radical treatments. The first step, says de Magalhaes, will be to grow human tissue with some of the mutations seen in the bowhead whale, Brandt&rsquo;s bat and naked mole rat. &ldquo;If we change human proteins to resemble it, we can see if it improves DNA repair,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;And I&rsquo;d like to take bowhead whale genes and put them in mice to see if they live longer.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-27"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Gene therapy could allow us to benefit from the helpful mutations that took millions of years to evolve","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-28"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter these initial tests, the next hurdle will be to find a way to create the same changes in the enormously complex human body, perhaps with drugs that mimic the effects of the genes. In some cases, you could genetically engineer organisms like yeast to churn out the relevant proteins in large vats that could then be purified for human use, or to find drugs that mimic the effects. In the future, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fghr.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fhandbook\u002Ftherapy\u002Fgenetherapy\"\u003Egene therapy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E could even allow us to tweak the DNA in living people; in an instant, we could benefit from the helpful mutations that took millions of years for the bowhead whale to evolve. Given the recent advances in gene therapy, he says &ldquo;there&rsquo;s no reason to think it&rsquo;s not a possibility further down the line.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClearly, there will be trials ahead. Although we are relatively closely related in evolutionary terms, what works in a whale, or naked mole rat, may have limited or no benefit in the human body. &ldquo;You can always find the different ways different organisms will suppress cancer &ndash; but whether they will be therapeutically useful, you just can&rsquo;t predict in advance,&rdquo; says Nunney. Nature&rsquo;s answers to cancer evolved in a &ldquo;serendipitous process&rdquo; he says, with haphazard solutions arising from each organism&rsquo;s unique circumstances. Even so, he welcomes this new approach to looking to nature for answers to medical issues. &ldquo;I think cancer biologists are beginning to recognise that incorporating evolutionary ideas can be a fruitful endeavour.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDe Magalhaes and Gladyshev are under no illusions about the arduous journey &ndash; but they remain hopeful. &ldquo;History is full of claims by experts that certain advances are impossible, only to be proven wrong soon after,&rdquo; says de Magalhaes. Consider the state of medicine just 120 years ago, when some of today&rsquo;s bowhead whales were still in their infancy. Back then life-threatening infections were just a fact of life. Today, antibiotics are taken for granted as the most basic healthcare.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltimately, de Magalhaes sees ageing as the ultimate disease &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC4203147\u002F\"\u003Ean illness that can be &ldquo;cured&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in its own right. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re not just extending the period of decrepitude,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;We want 70 year olds with the health of a 50 year old &ndash; that&rsquo;s the ultimate goal.&rdquo; Maybe, in 2120, we will look back with wonder at his first steps to reach that goal.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDavid Robson is BBC Future&rsquo;s feature writer. He is \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fd_a_robson\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E@d_a_robson\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E on Twitter.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFollow BBC Future on \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Finstagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002Fu\u002F0\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E and \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old-29"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2015-09-16T14:16:01Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","headlineLong":"The secrets of living to 200 years old","headlineShort":"The secrets of living to 200","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":null,"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Ageing is not an inevitable fact of life – many animals have already found ways to delay death. Their clues might help us all enjoy longer and healthier lives.","summaryShort":"Lessons in extreme longevity","tag":[],"textToSpeech":false,"creationDateTime":"2019-10-02T18:47:04.147977Z","entity":"article","guid":"f63d6cf0-17e6-4e7b-8bea-0633ee90f4c5","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old","modifiedDateTime":"2022-02-28T13:18:01.752388Z","project":"wwverticals","slug":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20150915-the-secrets-of-living-to-200-years-old","cacheLastUpdated":1665921288109},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing":{"urn":"urn:pubpipe:wwverticals:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing","_id":"62df801743d9f42c861a898f","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"Can meditation really slow down the effects of age? One Nobel Prize-winner is finding the scientific in the spiritual, writes Jo Marchant.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s seven in the morning on the beach in Santa Monica, California. The low sun glints off the waves and the clouds are still golden from the dawn. The view stretches out over thousands of miles of Pacific Ocean. In the distance, white villas of wealthy Los Angeles residents dot the Hollywood hills. Here by the shore, curlews and sandpipers cluster on the damp sand. A few metres back from the water&rsquo;s edge, a handful of people sit cross-legged: members of a local Buddhist centre about to begin an hour-long silent meditation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuch spiritual practices may seem a world away from biomedical research, with its focus on molecular processes and repeatable results. Yet just up the coast, at the University of California, San Francisco (UCSF), a team led by a Nobel Prize-winning biochemist is charging into territory where few mainstream scientists would dare to tread. Whereas Western biomedicine has traditionally shunned the study of personal experiences and emotions in relation to physical health, these scientists are placing state of mind at the centre of their work. They are engaged in serious studies hinting that meditation might &ndash; as Eastern traditions have long claimed &ndash; slow ageing and lengthen life.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EElizabeth Blackburn has always been fascinated by how life works. Born in 1948, she grew up by the sea in a remote town in Tasmania, Australia, collecting ants from her garden and jellyfish from the beach. When she began her scientific career, she moved on to dissecting living systems molecule by molecule.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWorking with biologist Joe Gall at Yale in the 1970s, Blackburn sequenced the chromosome tips of a single-celled freshwater creature called \u003Cem\u003ETetrahymena\u003C\u002Fem\u003E (&ldquo;pond scum&rdquo;, as she describes it) and discovered a repeating DNA motif that acts as a protective cap. The caps, dubbed telomeres, were subsequently found on human chromosomes too. They shield the ends of our chromosomes each time our cells divide and the DNA is copied, but they wear down with each division. In the 1980s, working with graduate student Carol Greider at the University of California, Berkeley, Blackburn discovered an enzyme called telomerase that can protect and rebuild telomeres. Even so, our telomeres dwindle over time. And when they get too short, our cells start to malfunction and lose their ability to divide &ndash; a phenomenon that is now recognised as a key process in ageing. This work ultimately won Blackburn the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn 2000, she received a visit that changed the course of her research. The caller was Elissa Epel, a postdoc from UCSF&rsquo;s psychiatry department. Psychiatrists and biochemists don&rsquo;t usually have much to talk about, but Epel was interested in the damage done to the body by chronic stress, and she had a radical proposal.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEpel, now director of the Aging, Metabolism and Emotion Center at UCSF, has a long-standing interest in how the mind and body relate. Her work, she says, is influenced by the holistic health guru Deepak Chopra, and the pioneering biologist Hans Selye, who first described in the 1930s how stressed rats can become chronically ill. &ldquo;Every stress leaves an indelible scar, and the organism pays for its survival after a stressful situation by becoming a little older,&rdquo; Selye said.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBack in 2000, Epel wanted to find that scar. &ldquo;I was interested in the idea that if we look deep within cells we might be able to measure the wear and tear of stress and daily life,&rdquo; she says. After reading about Blackburn&rsquo;s work on ageing, she wondered if telomeres might fit the bill.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E&lsquo;Another world&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003EWith some trepidation, she asked Blackburn for help with a study of mothers going through one of the most stressful situations that she could think of &ndash; caring for a chronically ill child. Epel&rsquo;s plan was to ask the women how stressed they felt, then look for a relationship between their state of mind and the state of their telomeres. Collaborators at the University of Utah would measure telomere length, while Blackburn&rsquo;s team would measure levels of telomerase.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlackburn&rsquo;s research until this point had involved elegant, precisely controlled experiments in the lab. Epel&rsquo;s work, on the other hand, was on real, complicated people living real, complicated lives. &ldquo;It was another world as far as I was concerned,&rdquo; says Blackburn. At first, she was doubtful that it would be possible to see any meaningful connection between stress and telomeres. Genes were seen as by far the most important factor determining telomere length, and the idea that it would be possible to measure environmental influences, let alone psychological ones, was highly controversial. But as a mother herself, Blackburn was drawn to the idea of studying the plight of these stressed women. &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t help but empathise.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt took four years before they were finally ready to collect blood samples from 58 women; this was a small pilot study. To give the highest chance of a meaningful result, the women in the two groups &ndash; stressed mothers and controls &ndash; had to match as closely as possible, with similar ages, lifestyles and backgrounds. Epel recruited her subjects with meticulous care. Still, Blackburn says, she saw the trial as nothing more than a feasibility exercise. Right up until Epel called her and said, &ldquo;You won&rsquo;t believe it.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe results were crystal clear. The more stressed the mothers said they were, the shorter their telomeres and the lower their levels of telomerase.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most frazzled women in the study had telomeres that translated into an extra decade or so of ageing compared to those who were least stressed, while their telomerase levels were halved. &ldquo;I was thrilled,&rdquo; says Blackburn. She and Epel had connected real lives and experiences to the molecular mechanics inside cells. It was the first indication that feeling stressed doesn&rsquo;t just damage our health &ndash; it literally ages us.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnexpected discoveries naturally meet scepticism. Blackburn and Epel struggled initially to publish their boundary-crossing paper. &ldquo;Science&nbsp;[one of the world&rsquo;s leading scientific journals] couldn&rsquo;t bounce it back fast enough!&rdquo; chuckles Blackburn.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResearch explosion\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003EWhen \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.pnas.org\u002Fcontent\u002F101\u002F49\u002F17312.full.pdf\"\u003Ethe paper finally was published\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, in the&nbsp;Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences&nbsp;in December 2004, it sparked widespread press coverage as well as praise. Robert Sapolsky, a pioneering stress researcher at Stanford University and author of the bestselling&nbsp;Why Zebras Don&rsquo;t Get Ulcers, described the collaboration as &ldquo;a leap across a vast interdisciplinary canyon&rdquo;. Mike Irwin, director of the Cousins Center for Psychoneuroimmunology at the University of California, Los Angeles, says it took a lot of courage for Epel to seek out Blackburn. &ldquo;And a lot of courage for Liz [Blackburn] to say yes.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany telomere researchers were wary at first. They pointed out that the study was small, and questioned the accuracy of the telomere length test used. &ldquo;This was a risky idea back then, and in some people&rsquo;s eyes unlikely,&rdquo; explains Epel. &ldquo;Everyone is born with very different telomere lengths and to think that we can measure something psychological or behavioural, not genetic, and have that predict the length of our telomeres? This is really not where this field was 10 years ago.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe paper triggered an explosion of research. Researchers have since linked perceived stress to shorter telomeres in healthy women as well as in Alzheimer&rsquo;s caregivers, victims of domestic abuse and early-life trauma, and people with major depression and post-traumatic stress disorder. &ldquo;Ten years on, there&rsquo;s no question in my mind that the environment has some consequence on telomere length,&rdquo; says Mary Armanios, a clinician and geneticist at Johns Hopkins School of Medicine who studies telomere disorders.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is also progress towards a mechanism. Lab studies show that the stress hormone cortisol reduces the activity of telomerase, while oxidative stress and inflammation &ndash; the physiological fallout of psychological stress &ndash; appear to erode telomeres directly.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis seems to have devastating consequences for our health. Age-related conditions from osteoarthritis, diabetes and obesity to heart disease, Alzheimer&rsquo;s and stroke have all been linked to short telomeres.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the decade since Blackburn and Epel&rsquo;s original study, the idea that stress ages us by eroding our telomeres has also permeated popular culture. In addition to Blackburn&rsquo;s many scientific accolades, she was named one of&nbsp;Time&nbsp;magazine&rsquo;s &ldquo;100 most influential people in the world&rdquo; in 2007, and received a&nbsp;Good Housekeeping achievement award in 2011. A workaholic character played by Cameron Diaz even described the concept in the 2006 Hollywood film&nbsp;The Holiday. &ldquo;It resonates,&rdquo; says Blackburn.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut as evidence of the damage caused by dwindling telomeres piles up, she is embarking on a new question: how to protect them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing stress\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E&nbsp;&ldquo;Ten years ago, if you&rsquo;d told me that I would be seriously thinking about meditation, I would have said one of us is loco,&rdquo; she told the\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003ENew York Times\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003Ein 2007. Since her initial study with Epel, the pair have become involved in collaborations with teams around the world &ndash; as many as 50 or 60, Blackburn estimates, spinning in &ldquo;wonderful directions&rdquo;. Many of these focus on ways to protect telomeres from the effects of stress; trials suggest that exercise, eating healthily and social support all help. But one of the most effective interventions, apparently capable of slowing the erosion of telomeres &ndash; and perhaps even lengthening them again &ndash; is meditation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESo far the studies are small, but they all tentatively point in the same direction. In one ambitious project, Blackburn and her colleagues sent participants to meditate at the Shambhala mountain retreat in northern Colorado. Those who completed a three-month-long course had 30% higher levels of telomerase than a similar group on a waiting list. A pilot study of dementia caregivers, carried out with UCLA&rsquo;s Irwin and published in 2013, found that volunteers who did an ancient chanting meditation called Kirtan Kriya, 12 minutes a day for eight weeks, had significantly higher telomerase activity than a control group who listened to relaxing music. And a collaboration with UCSF physician and self-help guru Dean Ornish, also published in 2013, found that men with low-risk prostate cancer who undertook comprehensive lifestyle changes, including meditation, kept their telomerase activity higher than similar men in a control group and had slightly longer telomeres after five years.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ETheories differ as to how meditation might boost telomeres and telomerase, but most likely it reduces stress. The practice involves slow, regular breathing, which may relax us physically by calming the fight-or-flight response. It probably has a psychological stress-busting effect too. Being able to step back from negative or stressful thoughts may allow us to realise that these are not necessarily accurate reflections of reality but passing, ephemeral events. It also helps us to appreciate the present instead of continually worrying about the past or planning for the future.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Being present in your activities and in your interactions is precious, and it&rsquo;s rare these days with all of the multitasking we do,&rdquo; says Epel. &ldquo;I do think that in general we&rsquo;ve got a society with scattered attention, particularly when people are highly stressed and don&rsquo;t have the resources to just be present wherever they are.&rdquo;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInevitably, when a Nobel Prize-winner starts talking about meditation, it ruffles a few feathers. In general, Blackburn&rsquo;s methodological approach to the topic has earned a grudging admiration, even among those who have expressed concern about the health claims made for alternative medicine. &ldquo;She goes about her business in a cautious and systematic fashion,&rdquo; says Edzard Ernst of the University of Exeter, UK, who specialises in testing complementary therapies in rigorous controlled trials. Oncologist James Coyne of the University of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia, who is sceptical of this field in general and describes some of the research on positive psychology and health as &ldquo;morally offensive&rdquo; and &ldquo;tooth fairy science&rdquo;, concedes that some of Blackburn&rsquo;s data is &ldquo;promising&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E&lsquo;Easy to be led astray&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003EOthers aren&rsquo;t so impressed. Surgeon-oncologist David Gorski is a well-known critic of alternative medicine and pseudoscience who blogs under the name of Orac &ndash; he&rsquo;s previously described Blackburn&rsquo;s collaborator Dean Ornish as &ldquo;one of the four horsemen of the Woo-pocalypse&rdquo;. Gorski stops short of pronouncing meditation as off-limits for scientific inquiry, but expresses concern that the preliminary results of these studies are being oversold. How can you be sure you&rsquo;re investigating it rigorously? &ldquo;It&rsquo;s really hard to do with these things,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;It is easy to be led astray. Nobel Prize-winners are not infallible.&rdquo; Blackburn&rsquo;s own biochemistry community also seems ambivalent about her interest in meditation. Three senior telomere researchers I contacted declined to discuss this aspect of her work, with one explaining that he didn&rsquo;t want to comment &ldquo;on such a controversial issue&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;People are very uncomfortable with the concept of meditation,&rdquo; notes Blackburn. She attributes this to its unfamiliarity and its association with spiritual and religious practices. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re always trying to say it as carefully as we can&hellip; always saying, &lsquo;look, it&rsquo;s preliminary, it&rsquo;s a pilot&rsquo;. But people won&rsquo;t even read those words. They&rsquo;ll see the newspaper headings and panic.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAny connotation of religious or paranormal beliefs makes many scientists uneasy, says Chris French, a psychologist at Goldsmiths, University of London, who studies anomalous experiences including altered states of consciousness. &ldquo;There are a lot of raised eyebrows, even though I&rsquo;ve got the word sceptic virtually tattooed across my forehead,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;It smacks of new-age woolly ideas for some people. There&rsquo;s a kneejerk dismissive response of &lsquo;we all know it&rsquo;s nonsense, why are you wasting your time?&rsquo;&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tide is now turning. Helped in part by money from the National Institute of Health (NIH), researchers have developed secularised &ndash; or non-religious &ndash; practices such as mindfulness-based stress reduction and mindfulness-based cognitive therapy, and reported a range of health effects from lowering blood pressure and boosting immune responses to warding off depression. And the past few years have seen a spurt of neuroscience studies showing that even short courses of meditation can forge structural changes in the brain.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlackburn&rsquo;s view is that meditation is a fair topic to study, as long as robust methods are used. So when her research first pointed in this direction, she was undaunted by concerns about what such studies might do to her reputation. Instead, she tried it out for herself, on an intensive six-day retreat in Santa Barbara. &ldquo;I loved it,&rdquo; she says. She still uses short bursts of meditation, which she says sharpen her mind and help her to avoid a busy, distracted mode. She even began one recent paper with a quote from the Buddha: &ldquo;The secret of health for both mind and body is not to mourn for the past, worry about the future, or anticipate troubles but to live in the present moment wisely and earnestly.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn September 2006, she attended a conference held at the Menla Mountain Buddhist centre, a remote retreat in New York&rsquo;s Catskill mountains, at which Western scientists met with Tibetan-trained scholars - including the Dalai Lama - to discuss longevity, regeneration and health. During the meeting, the spiritual leader honoured Blackburn&rsquo;s scientific achievements by inducting her as a &ldquo;Medicine Buddha&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlternative approach\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003EIf Epel&rsquo;s psychiatry research had been another world, the conference delegates' Eastern philosophy seemed to Blackburn more alien still. Over dinner one evening, while explaining to the other delegates how errors in the gene for telomerase can cause health problems, she described genetic mutation as a random, chance event. That&rsquo;s dogma for Western scientists but not for those trained in the Tibetan worldview. &ldquo;They said &lsquo;oh no, we don&rsquo;t regard this as chance&rsquo;,&rdquo; says Blackburn. For these holistic scholars, even the smallest events were infused with meaning. &ldquo;I suddenly thought, whoa, this is a very different world from the one I&rsquo;m on.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut instead of dismissing her Eastern counterparts, she was impressed. &ldquo;They&rsquo;re scholarly in a very different way, but it is still good-quality thinking,&rdquo; she explains. &ldquo;It wasn&rsquo;t &lsquo;God told me this&rsquo;, it was more &lsquo;let&rsquo;s see what actually happens in the brain&rsquo;. So there are certain elements of the approach that I am quite comfortable with as a scientist.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlackburn isn&rsquo;t tempted to embrace the spiritual approach herself. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m rooted in the physical world,&rdquo; she says. In general, Blackburn is more interested in how telomeres might help people directly, by encouraging them to live in a way that reduces their disease risk. &ldquo;This is not a familiar model for the medical world,&rdquo; she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EConventional medical tests give us our risk of particular conditions &ndash; high cholesterol warns of impending heart disease, for example, while high blood sugar predicts diabetes. Telomere length, by contrast, gives an overall reading of how healthy we are: our biological age. And although we already know that we should exercise, eat well and reduce stress, many of us fall short of these goals. Blackburn believes that putting a concrete number on how we are doing could provide a powerful incentive to change our behaviour. In fact, she and Epel have just completed a study (as yet unpublished) showing that simply being told their telomere length caused volunteers to live more healthily over the next year than a similar group who weren&rsquo;t told.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltimately, however, the pair want entire countries and governments to start paying attention to telomeres. More and more evidence shows that the stress from social adversity and inequality is a major force eroding these protective caps. People who didn&rsquo;t finish high school or are in an abusive relationship have shorter telomeres, for example, while studies have also shown links with low socioeconomic status, shift work, lousy neighbourhoods and environmental pollution. Children are particularly at risk: being abused or experiencing adversity early in life leaves people with shorter telomeres for the rest of their lives. And through telomeres, the stress that women experience during pregnancy affects the health of the next generation too, causing hardship and economic costs for decades to come.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpeaking out\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn 2012, Blackburn and Epel wrote a commentary in the journal&nbsp;Nature, listing some of these results and calling on politicians to prioritise &ldquo;societal stress reduction&rdquo;. In particular, they argued, improving the education and health of women of child-bearing age could be &ldquo;a highly effective way to prevent poor health filtering down through generations&rdquo;. Meditation retreats or yoga classes might help those who can afford the time and expense, they pointed out. &ldquo;But we are talking about broad socioeconomic policies to buffer the chronic stressors faced by so many.&rdquo; Where many scientists refrain from discussing the political implications of their work, Blackburn says she wanted to speak out on behalf of women who lack support, and say &ldquo;You&rsquo;d better take their situations seriously.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20140701-can-meditation-delay-ageing-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile arguments for tackling social inequality are hardly new, Blackburn says that telomeres allow us to quantify for the first time the health impact of stress and inequality and therefore the resulting economic costs. We can also now pinpoint pregnancy and early childhood as &ldquo;imprinting periods&rdquo; when telomere length is particularly susceptible to stress. Together, she says, this evidence makes a stronger case than ever before for governments to act.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut it seems that most scientists and politicians still aren&rsquo;t ready to leap across the interdisciplinary canyon that Blackburn and Epel bridged a decade ago. The&nbsp;Nature article has engendered little response, according to a frustrated Epel. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a strong statement so I would have thought that people would have criticised it or supported it,&rdquo; says Epel. &ldquo;Either way!&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It&rsquo;s now a consistent story that the ageing machinery is shaped at the earliest stages of life,&rdquo; she insists. &ldquo;If we ignore that and we just keep trying to put band-aids on later, we&rsquo;re never going to get at prevention and we&rsquo;re only going to fail at cure.&rdquo; Simply responding to the physical symptoms of disease might make sense for treating an acute infection or fixing a broken leg, but to beat chronic age-related conditions such as diabetes, heart disease and dementia, we will need to embrace the fuzzy, subjective domain of the mind.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThis is an edited version of an article originally published by Mosaic, and is reproduced under a Creative Commons licence. For more about the issues around this story, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.mosaicscience.com\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003Evisit Mosaic&rsquo;s website here\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you would like