rn":"urn:pubpipe:wwverticals:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men","_id":"62df7fec43d9f4054968a265","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"All across the world, women enjoy longer lifespans. David Robson investigates the reasons why, and whether men can do anything about it.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs soon as I was born, I was already destined to die earlier than half the babies in my maternity ward &ndash; a curse that I can do little to avoid. The reason? My sex. Simply due to the fact that I am male, I can be expected to die around three years earlier than a woman born on the same day.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhat is it about being a man that means I am likely to die younger than the women around me? And is it possible for me to break the curse of my gender? Although this puzzling divide has been known for decades, it is only recently that we have started coming close to some answers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne early idea was that men work themselves into an early grave. Whether working in a mine or ploughing the land, they put extra stress on their bodies and amassed injuries that caught up with them later in life. Yet if that were the case, you might expect the gap to be closing, as both men and women converge on the same, sedentary jobs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The survival advantage of women is seen in every country, in every year, for which reliable records exist","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn fact, the difference in lifespan has remained stable even throughout monumental shifts in society. Consider Sweden, which offers the most reliable historic records. In 1800, life expectancy at birth was 33 years for women and 31 years for men; today it is 83.5 years and 79.5 years, respectively. In both cases, women live about 5% longer than men. As \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.karger.com\u002FArticle\u002FFullText\u002F381472\"\u003Eone recent article put it\u003C\u002Fa\u003E: &ldquo;This remarkably consistent survival advantage of women compared with men in early life, in late life, and in total life is seen in every country in every year for which reliable birth and death records exist. There may be no more robust pattern in human biology.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENor has it been easy to prove that men are more abusive of their bodies. Factors \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flkyspp.nus.edu.sg\u002Fips\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002Fsites\u002F2\u002F2014\u002F04\u002FForum_Why-women-live-longer-than-men_280314.pdf\"\u003Esuch as smoking, drinking, and overeating\u003C\u002Fa\u003E may partly explain why size of the gender gap varies so widely between countries. Russian men are likely to die 13 years earlier than Russian women, for instance, partly because \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002Fs10654-014-9893-4\"\u003Ethey drink and smoke more heavily\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. But the fact is that female chimpanzees, gorillas, orangutans, and gibbons also consistently outlive the males of the group, and you do not see apes &ndash; male or female &ndash; with cigarettes hanging out of their mouths and beer glasses in their hands.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInstead, it would seem like the answer lies in our evolution. &ldquo;Of course, social and lifestyle factors do have a bearing, but there does appear to be something deeper engrained in our biology,&rdquo; says Tom Kirkwood, who studies the biological basis for ageing at Newcastle University in the UK.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are many potential mechanisms &ndash; starting with the bundles of DNA known as chromosomes within each cell. Chromosomes come in pairs, and whereas women have two X chromosomes, men have an X and a Y chromosome.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"A woman&rsquo;s heart rate increases during the menstrual cycle, offering the same benefits as moderate exercise","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThat difference may subtly alter the way that cells age. Having two X chromosomes, women keep double copies of every gene, meaning they have a spare if one is faulty. Men don&rsquo;t have that back-up. The result is that more cells may begin to malfunction with time, putting men at greater risk of disease.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmong the other alternatives is the &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fpii\u002FS0301211507000395\"\u003Ejogging female heart\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo; hypothesis &ndash; the idea that a woman&rsquo;s heart rate increases during the second half of the menstrual cycle, offering the same benefits as moderate exercise. The result is delayed risk of cardiovascular disease later in life. Or it could also be a simple matter of size. Taller people have more cells in their bodies, meaning they are \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20150928-tall-vs-small-which-is-it-better-to-be\"\u003Emore likely to develop harmful mutations\u003C\u002Fa\u003E; bigger bodies also burn more energy, which could add to wear and tear within the tissues themselves. Since men tend to be taller than women, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F12586217\"\u003Ethey should therefore face more long-term damage\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Eunuchs were 130 times more likely to reach 100, compared to other men. Even the pampered kings did not come close","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut perhaps the true reason lies in the testosterone that drives most other male characteristics, from deeper voices and hairier chests to balding crowns. Evidence comes from an unexpected place: the Imperial Court of the Chosun Dynasty in Korea. Korean scientist Han-Nam Park recently analysed the detailed records of court life from the 19th Century, including information about 81 eunuchs whose testicles had been removed before puberty. His analyses revealed that the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedirect.com\u002Fscience\u002Farticle\u002Fpii\u002FS0960982212007129\"\u003Eeunuchs lived for around 70 years\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; compared to an average of just 50 years among the other men in the court. Overall, they were 130 times more likely to celebrate their hundredth birthday than the average man living in Korea at the time. Even the kings &ndash; who were the most pampered people in the palace &ndash; did not come close.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough not all studies of other types of eunuch have shown such pronounced differences, overall it seems that people (and animals) without testicles do live longer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe exact reasons are elusive, but David Gems at University College London \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3969277\u002F\"\u003Especulates that the damage may be done by the end of puberty\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. For speculative evidence, he points to the sad cases of mental health patients, institutionalised in the USA in the early 20th Century. A few were forcibly castrated as part of their &ldquo;treatment&rdquo;. Like the Korean eunuchs, they too lived for longer than the average inmate &ndash; but only if they had been sterilised before the age of 15. Testosterone might make our bodies stronger in the short-term, but the same changes also leave us open to heart disease, infections, and cancer later in life. &ldquo;For example, testosterone might increase seminal fluid production but promote prostate cancer; or it might alter cardiovascular function in a way that improves performance early in life but leads to hypertension and atherosclerosis later,&rdquo; says Gem.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ENot only do women escape the risks of testosterone &ndash; they may also benefit from their own &ldquo;elixir of youth&rdquo; that helps heal some of the ravages of time. The \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fsageke.sciencemag.org\u002Fcgi\u002Fcontent\u002Ffull\u002F2005\u002F23\u002Fpe17\"\u003Efemale sex hormone oestrogen is an &ldquo;antioxidant&rdquo;,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E meaning that it mops up poisonous chemicals that cause cells stress. In animal experiments, females lacking oestrogen tend not to live so long as those who have not been operated on &ndash; the exact opposite of the male eunuch&rsquo;s fate. &ldquo;If you remove a rodents&rsquo; ovaries, then the cells don&rsquo;t repair against molecular damage quite as well,&rdquo; says Kirkwood.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Once the children are born, the men are more disposable","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EKirkwood and Gem both think of this as a kind of evolutionary pay-off that gave both men and women the best chances of passing on their genes. During mating, women would be more likely to go for alpha males, pumped up on testosterone. But once the children are born, the men are more disposable, says Kirkwood. &ldquo;The welfare of offspring is intimately connected with welfare of the maternal body. The bottom line is that it matters more for the children that the mother&rsquo;s body should be in good shape, rather than the father&rsquo;s.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat&rsquo;s cold comfort for men today. As it is, the scientists admit that we need to keep on looking for a definitive answer. &ldquo;We really have to retain an open mind as to how much the difference can be explained by hormonal differences and other factors,&rdquo; says Kirkwood. But the hope is that eventually, the knowledge may provide some hints to help us all live a little longer.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDavid Robson is BBC Future&rsquo;s feature writer. He is \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fd_a_robson\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E@d_a_robson\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&nbsp;\u003Cem\u003Eon Twitter.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFollow us\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Cem\u003Eon\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fbbc_future\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fplus.google.com\u002F107828172298602173375\u002Fposts\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoogle+\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E,&nbsp;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.linkedin.com\u002Fcompany\u002Fbbc-com\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELinkedIn\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Cem\u003Eand \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Finstagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men-15"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2015-10-02T00:18:56Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","headlineLong":"Why do women live longer than men?","headlineShort":"Why do women live longer than men?","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":null,"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"All across the world, women enjoy longer lifespans. So why are men cursed with early deaths, asks David Robson.","summaryShort":"And can men do anything about it?","tag":[],"textToSpeech":false,"creationDateTime":"2019-10-02T18:48:13.110896Z","entity":"article","guid":"6d069dd2-c2f8-4f33-9e36-290e4a8103c0","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men","modifiedDateTime":"2022-02-24T16:41:51.267215Z","project":"wwverticals","slug":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20151001-why-women-live-longer-than-men","cacheLastUpdated":1665921288109},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less":{"urn":"urn:pubpipe:wwverticals:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less","_id":"62df7fd143d9f46d95451e6d","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Falex-riley"],"bodyIntro":"Permanently cutting the daily calories you consume may turn out to have a profound effect on your future life, according to some tantalising scientific studies.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fcolumns\u002Flockdown-longreads\"\u003E\u003Cimg src=\"https:\u002F\u002Fichef.bbci.co.uk\u002Fimages\u002Fic\u002Fraw\u002Fp08fbgv3.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"&ldquo;The\" width=\"100%\" \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBBC Future has brought you in-depth and rigorous stories to help you navigate the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Ftags\u002Fcovid-19\"\u003Ecurrent pandemic\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, but we know that&rsquo;s not all you want to read. So now we&rsquo;re dedicating a series to help you escape. We&rsquo;ll be revisiting our most popular features from the last three years in our \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELockdown Longreads\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.&nbsp;&nbsp; \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou&rsquo;ll find everything from the story about the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20170818-voyager-inside-the-worlds-greatest-space-mission\"\u003Eworld&rsquo;s greatest space mission\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to the truth about whether \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20191024-why-do-we-think-cats-are-unfriendly\"\u003Eour cats really love us\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, the epic hunt to bring \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20190213-the-dramatic-hunt-for-the-fish-pirates-exploiting-our-seas\"\u003Eillegal fishermen to justice\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and the small team which brings \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20180312-the-salvagers-who-raise-world-war-two-tanks-from-the-dead\"\u003Elong-buried World War Two tanks back to life\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. What you won&rsquo;t find is any reference to, well, you-know-what. Enjoy.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn a restaurant setting sometime in the not-too distant future, a man and a woman are on their first date. After the initial nerves subside, all is going well.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe man is 33, he says, has been single for most of those years, and, although he doesn&rsquo;t mention it, knows he is looking to settle down and have a family. The woman replies that she is 52, has been married, divorced, and has children in their early 20s. He had no idea &ndash; she looked his age, or younger.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis is a dream of Julie Mattison from the National Institute on Ageing (NIA) in the United States. She envisions a time when chronological age ticks by with every year, but biological age can be set to a different timer, where elderly doesn&rsquo;t mean what it does now.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIt sounds far-fetched, but our society has already made great strides towards that goal, thanks to advances in medicine and improvements in healthy living. In 2014, for instance, the United States Health Interview Survey reported that 16% of people aged between 50 and 64 were impaired every day with chronic illness. Three decades earlier that number was 23%. In other words, as well as benefiting from longer lifespans, we are also experiencing longer &ldquo;healthspans&rdquo; &ndash; and the latter is proving to be even more malleable. To paraphrase and update a speech from John F Kennedy given at the first White House Conference on Ageing in 1961, life can indeed be added to years, rather than just years added to life.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Healthspan is proving to be even more malleable than lifespan &nbsp;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ESo, what do we need to do to enhance the length and quality of our lives even more? Researchers worldwide are \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fscience\u002F0\u002F22019289\"\u003Epursuing various ideas\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, but for Mattison and colleagues, the answer is a simple change in diet. They believe that the key to a better old age may be to reduce the amount of food on our plates, via an approach called &ldquo;calorie restriction&rdquo;. This diet goes further than cutting back on fatty foods from time-to-time; it&rsquo;s about making gradual and careful reductions&nbsp;in portion&nbsp;size permanently. Since the early 1930s, a 30% reduction in the amount of food consumed per day has been linked to longer, more active lives in worms, flies, rats, mice, and monkeys. Across the animal kingdom, in other words, calorie restriction has proven the best remedy for the ravages of life. And it&rsquo;s possible that humans have just as much to gain.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p054l91b"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe idea that what a person eats influences their health no doubt predates any historical accounts that remain today. But, as is often the case for any scientific discipline, the first detailed accounts come from Ancient Greece. Hippocrates, one of the first physicians to claim diseases were natural and not supernatural, observed that many ailments were associated with gluttony; obese Greeks tended to die younger than slim Greeks, that was clear and written down on papyrus.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpreading from this epicentre of science, these ideas were adopted and adapted over the centuries. And at the end of the 15th Century, Alvise Cornaro, an infirm aristocrat from a small village near Venice in Italy, turned the prevailing wisdom on its head, and on himself.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf indulgence was harmful, would dietary asceticism be helpful? To find out, Cornaro, aged 40, ate only 350g (12oz) of food per day, roughly 1000 calories according to recent estimates. He ate bread, panatela or broth, and eggs. For meat he chose veal, goat, beef, partridge, thrush, and any poultry that was available. He bought fish caught from the local rivers.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERestricted in amount but not variety, Cornaro claimed to have achieved &ldquo;perfect health&rdquo; up until his death more than 40 years later. Although he changed his birthdate as he aged, claiming that he had reached his 98th year, it is thought that he was around 84 when he died &ndash; still an impressive feat in the 16th Century, a time when 50 or 60 years old was considered elderly. In 1591, his grandson published his posthumous three-volume tome entitled &ldquo;Discourses on the Sober Life,&rdquo; pushing dietary restriction into the mainstream, and redefining ageing itself.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith an additional boost of health into the evening of life, the elderly, in full possession of their mental capacities, would be able to put decades of amassed knowledge to good use, Carnaro claimed. With his diet, beauty became the aged, not the youthful.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELongevity trials\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECornaro was an interesting man but his findings are not to be taken as fact by any branch of science. Even if he was true to his word and did not suffer ill health for nearly half a century, which seems unlikely, he was a case study of one &ndash; not representative of humans as a whole.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut since a foundational study in 1935 in white rats, a dietary restriction of between 30-50% has been shown to extend lifespan, delaying death from age-related disorders and disease. Of course, what works for a rat or any other laboratory organism might not work for a human.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p054l8y3"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ELong-term trials, following humans from early adulthood to death, are a rarity. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t see a human study of longevity as something that would be a fundable research programme,&rdquo; says Mattison. &ldquo;Even if you start humans at 40 or 50 years old, you&rsquo;re still looking at potentially 40 or 50 more years [of study].&rdquo; Plus, she adds, ensuring that extraneous factors &ndash; exercise, smoking, medical treatments, mental wellbeing &ndash; don&rsquo;t influence the trial&rsquo;s end results is near impossible for our socially and culturally complex species.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThat&rsquo;s why, in the late 1980s, two independent long-term trials &ndash; one at NIA and the other at the University of Wisconsin &ndash; were set up to study calorie restriction and ageing in Rhesus monkeys. Not only do we share 93% of our DNA with these primates, we age in the same way too.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESlowly, after middle age (around 15 years in Rhesus monkeys) the back starts to hunch, the skin and muscles start to sag, and, where it still grows, hair goes from gingery brown to grey. The similarities go deeper. In these primates, the occurrence of cancer, diabetes, and heart disease increases in frequency and severity with age. &ldquo;They&rsquo;re an excellent model to study ageing,&rdquo; says Rozalyn Anderson, a gerontologist from the University of Wisconsin.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Sherman is the oldest Rhesus monkey ever recorded, nearly 20 years older than the average lifespan for his species in captivity &nbsp;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnd they&rsquo;re easy to control. Fed with specially made biscuits, the diets of the 76 monkeys at the University of Wisconsin and the 121 at NIA are tailored to their age, weight, and natural appetite. All monkeys receive the full complement of nutrients and minerals that their bodies crave. It&rsquo;s just that half of the monkeys, the calorie restricted (or CR) group, eat 30% less.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey are far from malnourished or starving. Take Sherman, a 43-year-old monkey from NIA. Mattison says that since being placed on the CR diet in 1987, aged 16, Sherman hasn&rsquo;t shown any overt signs of hunger that are well characterised in his species.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p054l8y7"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan\u003ESherman is the oldest Rhesus monkey ever recorded, nearly 20 years older than the average lifespan for his species in captivity. As younger monkeys were developing diseases and dying, he seemed to be immune to ageing. Even into his 30s he would have been considered an old monkey, but he didn&rsquo;t look or act like one.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe same is true, to varying extents, for the rest of his experimental troop at NIA. &ldquo;We have a lower incidence of diabetes, and lower incidence of cancer in the CR groups,&rdquo; says Mattison. In 2009, the University of Wisconsin trial published similarly spectacular results.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENot only did their CR monkeys look remarkably younger &ndash; with more hair, less sag, and brown instead of grey &ndash; than monkeys that were fed a standard diet, they were healthier on the inside too, free from pathology. Cancers, such as the common intestinal adenocarcinoma, were reduced by over 50%. The risk of heart disease was similarly halved. And while 11 of the \u003Cem\u003Ead libitum\u003C\u002Fem\u003E (&ldquo;at one&rsquo;s pleasure,&rdquo; in Latin) monkeys developed diabetes and five exhibited signs that they were pre-diabetic, the blood glucose regulation seemed healthy in all CR monkeys. For them, diabetes wasn&rsquo;t a thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOverall, only 13% of the monkeys in the CR group had died of age-related causes in 20 years. In the \u003Cem\u003Ead libitum\u003C\u002Fem\u003E group, 37% had died, nearly three times as many. In an update study from the University of Wisconsin in 2014, this percentage remained stable.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The results show that ageing itself is a reasonable target for clinical intervention and medical treatment &ndash; Rozalyn Anderson &nbsp;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We have demonstrated that ageing can be manipulated in primates,&rdquo; says Anderson. &ldquo;It kind of gets glossed over because it&rsquo;s obvious, but conceptually that&rsquo;s hugely important; it means that ageing itself is a reasonable target for clinical intervention and medical treatment.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf ageing can be delayed, in other words, all of the diseases associated with it will follow suit. &ldquo;Going after each disease one at a time isn&rsquo;t going to significantly extend lifespan for people because they&rsquo;ll die of something else,&rdquo; says Anderson. &ldquo;If you cured all cancers, you wouldn&rsquo;t offset death due to cardiovascular disease, or dementia, or diabetes-associated disorders. Whereas if you go after ageing you can offset the lot in one go.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p054l90v"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EEating less certainly seemed to help the monkeys, but calorie restriction is much tougher for people out in the real world. For one, our access to regular, high-calorie meals is now easier than ever; with companies like Deliveroo and UberEats, there is no longer a need to walk to the restaurant anymore. And two, gaining weight simply comes more naturally to some people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;There&rsquo;s a huge genetic component to all of this and its much harder work for some people than it is for others to stay trim,&rdquo; says Anderson. &ldquo;We all know someone who can eat an entire cake and nothing happens, they look the exact same. And then someone else walks past a table with a cake \u003Cem\u003Eon it\u003C\u002Fem\u003E and they have to go up a pant size.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIdeally, the amount and types of food we eat should be tailored to who we are &ndash; our genetic predisposition to gaining weight, how we metabolise sugars, how we store fat, and other physiological fluxes that are beyond the scope of scientific instruction at the moment, and perhaps forever.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut a predisposition to obesity can be used as a guide to life choices rather than an inevitability. &ldquo;I personally have a genetic history of obesity running through my family, and I practice a flexible form of caloric restriction,&rdquo; says \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fhnrca.tufts.edu\u002Fpeople\u002Fscientists\u002Fq-z\u002Fsusan-b-roberts-ph-d\u002F\"\u003ESusan Roberts\u003C\u002Fa\u003E a dietary scientist at Tufts University in Boston. &ldquo;I keep my BMI at 22, and [have calculated] that that requires eating 80% of what I would eat if my BMI was at 30 like every other member of my family.&rdquo; Roberts stresses that it isn&rsquo;t hard &ndash; she follows her own weight management programme using \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Ftheidiet.com\u002F\"\u003Ea tool called iDiet\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to help her eat less but avoid feeling hungry or deprived of enjoyment. If this wasn&rsquo;t possible, she adds, she wouldn&rsquo;t practise calorie restriction.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENot only has Roberts seen the problems of obesity first-hand in her family, she knows the benefits of CR better than most. For over 10 years she has been a leading scientist in the Comprehensive Assessment of Long-Term Effects of Reducing Intake of Energy trial, also known as Calerie. Over two years, 218 healthy men and women aged between 21 and 50 years were split into two groups.&nbsp; In one, people were allowed to eat as they normally would (\u003Cem\u003Ead libitum\u003C\u002Fem\u003E), while the other ate 25% less (CR). Both had health checks every six months.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike in the Rhesus monkey trials, tests over two years can&rsquo;t determine whether CR reduces or delays age-related diseases. There simply isn&rsquo;t enough time for their development. But the Calerie trials tested for the next best thing: the early biological signs of heart disease, cancer, and diabetes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPublished in 2015, the results after two years were very positive. In the blood of calorie-restricted people, the ratio of &ldquo;good&rdquo; cholesterol to &ldquo;bad&rdquo; cholesterol had increased, molecules associated with tumour formation &ndash; called tumour necrosis factors (TNFs) &ndash; were reduced by around 25%, and levels of insulin resistance, a sure sign of diabetes, fell by nearly 40% compared to people who ate their normal diets. Overall, the blood&rsquo;s pressure was lower.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Significant health benefits may be garnered in an already healthy body, but further trials are needed &nbsp;","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAdmittedly, some benefits may come from weight-loss. Earlier trials from Calerie had included people that were obese as well as those with a healthy body mass index (BMI) of 25 or below, and slimming down would have certainly improved the welfare of the heavier participants. &ldquo;One thing that&rsquo;s been very clear for a long time is that being overweight or obese is bad for you,&rdquo; says Roberts. Diseases and disorders previously thought to be age-associated diseases are now popping up in the obese population, she adds.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut the latest results suggested that significant health benefits can be garnered in an already healthy body &ndash; a person who isn&rsquo;t underweight or obese. That is, someone whose BMI lies between 18.5 and 25.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite these results, evidence from further trials will be needed before someone with an already healthy BMI should be advised to reduce their calorie intake. (And anyone wanting to change their diet would be advised to consult a medical professional beforehand.)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p054l8v8"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the meantime, the scientists will be hoping that their rhesus macaques may help us to understand exactly why calories restriction may have these effects. With nearly 30 years of data on lives and deaths, and blood and tissue samples, from nearly 200 monkeys, the work at NIA and the University of Wisconsin aim to shine a light into the black box of calorie restriction, illuminating just how it delays ageing.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith less food, is the metabolism forced to be more efficient with what it has? Is there a common molecular switch regulating ageing that is turned on (or off) with fewer calories? Or is there an as of yet unknown mechanism underpinning our lives and deaths? The importance of monkeys like Sherman far outspans their lives.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-18"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Calorie restriction may be one of the most promising avenues for improving health and how long it lasts in our lives","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20170601-the-secret-to-a-long-and-healthy-life-eat-less-19"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnswers to such questions might be long in coming. &ldquo;If I cloned 10 of myself and we all worked furiously, I don&rsquo;t think we&rsquo;d have it solved,&rdquo; says Anderson. &ldquo;The biology is inordinately complicated.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s a worthwhile undertaking &ndash; understand how CR works and other treatments could then be used to target that specific part of our biology. Ageing could be treated directly, that is, without the need of calorie restriction. &ldquo;And I think that&rsquo;s really the golden ticket,&rdquo; says Anderson.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough lacking a neat explanation, calorie restriction is one of the most promising avenues for improving health and how long it lasts in our lives. &ldquo;There was nothing in what we saw that made us think caloric restriction doesn&rsquo;t work in people,&rdquo; says Roberts, from the Calerie trial. And, unlike drug-based treatments, it doesn&rsquo;t come with a long list of possible side effects. &ldquo;Our people were not hungrier, their mood was fine, their sexual function was fine. We looked pretty hard for bad things and didn&rsquo;t find them,&rdquo; says Roberts.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne expected issue was a slight decrease in bone density that is often tied to gradual weight loss, says Roberts. But as a precaution, volunteers were provided with small calcium supplements throughout the trial.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEven with such promising findings, &ldquo;this [the Calerie trial] is the first study of its kind, and I don&rsquo;t think that any of us would feel confident in saying, &lsquo;okay, we&rsquo;re going to recommend this to everyone in the world,&rsquo;&rdquo; says Roberts. &ldquo;But it&rsquo;s a really exciting prospect. I think that delaying the progression of chronic diseases is something that everyone can get behind and get excited about, because nobody wants to live life with one of those.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAlex Riley is a writer based in Berlin, Germany. He tweets as&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Friley__alex\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E@riley__alex\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDisclaimer\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003EAll content within this story is provided for general information only, and should not be treated as a substitute for the medical advice of your own doctor or 